# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beauty-without-cruelty
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] It is a foundational essay advocating for vegetarianism, maintaining that a plant-based diet is essential for bodily health, moral virtue, and social justice.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that meat consumption is unnatural, a "slow but certain poison", causing disease, which "pollutes" the body, and leads to vice and depravity.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He prescribes the return to a "natural" vegetable diet.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This work is regarded as one of the earliest and most fervent defenses of vegetarianism in English literature.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley wrote four essays on the subject of vegetarianism, "A Vindication of Natural Diet" (1813), the note in *Queen Mab*, in a section of "A Refutation of Deism" (1814), and "On the Vegetable System of Diet", which was published posthumously in 1929.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley first experimented with a vegetarian diet while at the University of Oxford according to Thomas Jefferson Hogg.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began a vegetarian diet on 1 March 1812 along with his first wife Harriet Westbrook.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began composing the essay in October–November 1812.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley met John Frank Newton during 1812-1813 and influenced his views on vegetarianism.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Historian Keith Thomas has noted that Newton's *Return to Nature* "provided much of the basis" for Shelley's *A Vindication of Natural Diet*.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The work has been republished since 1813, beginning with an abridged version which was published in Boston by March, Capen, and Lyon in an American collection *Vegetable Diet: As Sanctioned by Medical Men, and by Experience in All Ages*, edited by William A.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The essay was reprinted in 1884 in a new edition in London by Frederick Pitman and by John Heywood and the Vegetarian Society in Manchester.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The original title page was reproduced: *A Vindication of Natural Diet.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Being One in a Series of Notes to Queen Mab (A Philosophical Poem).* London: Printed for J.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The new edition featured a preface by Henry Stephens Salt and William Axon.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In 1904, the work was republished in London by C.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Daniel as *A Vindication of Natural Diet and Extracts from the Works of Dr.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley used the imagery of slaughtering a lamb.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In the novel *Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus* (1818), which he is acknowledged to have contributed to, the Being is portrayed as a vegetarian.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The Being explained his vegetarian diet to Victor Frankenstein: "My food is not that of man.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment." Shelley's views on vegetarianism are routinely incorrectly attributed to his wife.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *Laon and Cythna*, republished as *The Revolt of Islam* (1817), Fifth Canto, the Festival of nations held after the Revolution is a banquet where no meat is served.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The feast is vegetarian: "Never again may blood of bird or beast/ Stain with its venomous stream a human feast".
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This is "The banquet of the free" where the guests are described as "reclining as they ate, of Liberty,/ And Hope, and Justice".
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The festival was not polluted by gore, "But piled on high, an overflowing store/ Of pomegranates, and citrons, fairest fruit,/ Melons, and dates, and figs, and many a root".
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was unnatural.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He maintained that diseases and immorality arose from mankind's "unnatural habits of life".
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] A meatless diet was the best regimen for maintaining a healthy and disease-free lifestyle.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He wrote that human diseases could be decreased by a return to a natural vegetable diet.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was a practice that polluted the body with syphilis and resulted in other ailments.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *A Vindication of Natural Diet* he wrote, "Should ever a physician be born with the genius of Locke, I am persuaded that he might trace all bodily and mental derangements to our unnatural habits," these unnatural habits being the consumption of meat.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He cited the allegory of Prometheus who stole fire from the gods which enabled mankind to cook meat, thereby screening the disgust and horror of dead flesh.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He concluded that a person with compassion and empathy for animals, "rising from a meal of roots", would be able to maintain a healthy and balanced diet and lifestyle.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley presented examples of how a vegetarian diet resulted in longevity and an increased lifespan.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The only threat of death will be that of natural, old age, that "old age would be our last and our only malady".
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The two rules he prescribes for a natural diet are to never eat anything that was alive and to drink only distilled water.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] In 1963, Dowding set up **Beauty Without Cruelty Limited** (BWC Ltd), the trading branch of the charity, so their cruelty-free cosmetics and other products, including simulated furs could be sold.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] The charity, now known as the BWC Charitable Trust, established branches in Australia, New Zealand, India, South Africa, United States, Canada, Scotland, Wales, Ireland, the Netherlands, Kenya, Rhodesia, Japan, Finland and Hong Kong.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] The first Beauty Without Cruelty boutique opened in central London in 1965.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Currently two independently run BWC charitable organisations are in existence having expanded the scope of work: **Beauty Without Cruelty – India** and **Beauty Without Cruelty (South Africa)**.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] There are also two independent cruelty-free cosmetic companies: **Beauty Without Cruelty** in the United Kingdom and **Beauty Without Cruelty** in the United States.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] These are vegan and continue to refuse to test their products on animals.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Dowding, dedicated to the rights of animals, was appalled by the suffering and cruelty involved in the production of fur coats and fur accessories, fashionable at the time.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] In 1959, she explored the alternatives to fur and set out to make known her findings to the wider public.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] With friends, Sylvia Barbanell, Olive Burton, Elspeth Douglas Reid, Dr Barbara Latto and Monica Latto drawn into the idea they formed a small volunteer committee to stage fashion shows featuring simulated furs bearing the label ‘*Beauty Without Cruelty*’.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] They exposed the cruelty behind the barbaric fur trade in order to change public opinion, whilst also demonstrating the suffering inflicted on animals.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] The first London fashion show caused much publicity and was a great success, leading to subsequent events in England.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] People began writing to Dowding, and national papers, radio and television picked up on the story and the movement escalated, becoming clear that many were anxious to help.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] BWC tried to remain a movement, that worked alongside other animal welfare groups and organisations, not another society in competition with others.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] As interest grew, they began a periodical newsletter to keep in touch with their many supporters.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] BWC's campaign to make fake furs socially acceptable and virtuous made an effective contribution to the development of fake fur, as each season brought advances to the quality of their fabrics.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Alongside BWC's exposure of the fur trade, Dowding brought the public's attention to the use of animal ingredients in cosmetics, which were obtained in no less of a cruel and ruthless manner.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] She learnt a closely guarded trade secret, that cosmetic companies also tested their products on animals, on a very large scale, often in horrific ways.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] This knowledge led to an important part of BWC's early work, examining claims made by manufacturers that their products were free from cruelty.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Cosmetic products, where necessary were tested and analysed by BWC's technical adviser, a well-known cosmetic chemist, Mr.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] James, as at that time no labelling requirements were laid down for cosmetics contents, although manufactured foodstuff required this by law.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] BWC (U.S.A.) later followed suit publishing its own guide listing cruelty-free companies.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] The minimal profit made from this was ploughed back into making the next product and so on.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Eventually through trial and error, Long, on behalf of BWC, developed the first full range of cruelty-free cosmetics, created from the finest oils and essences of plants, herbs and flowers.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Long continued working with BWC until her death in 1970.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] According to Dowding, BWC pioneered the production of 100 percent vegetable soap as a luxury item.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] As charities could not enter trade, he also created a limited company, **Beauty Without Cruelty Ltd**, under which the cruelty-free products they promoted and manufactured could be sold.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] All profits from the cruelty-free sales went back to the charity.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Dowding searched unsuccessfully for a shop that would have a Beauty Without Cruelty counter, due to the conflict of interest with many of the established cosmetic firms.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] In 1963, a small BWC boutique was opened in a committee member's garage in Bayswater, London, selling the cruelty- free products.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] In 1965, BWC bought and opened its first boutique at 49 Upper Montagu Street, London.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Affiliated branches began opening boutiques in Britain enabling more people access to cruelty-free clothes and cosmetics.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] A quarterly journal, *Compassion*, covered BWC's activities and published articles on kindred subjects in the wider humanitarian field.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] A kinship with all forms of life was encouraged.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] The public was reached through newspaper and magazine articles, television and radio in Britain and abroad.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Fashion and film shows, exhibitions and public meetings were held.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Council members and other qualified speakers addressed interested societies and organisations.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] By 1962, BWC had established branches in Australia**,** Japan**,** the United States and New Zealand, and Canada in 1963.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] In the United Kingdom**,** a Northern and a Scottish branch started in 1965.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] The Rhodesian and South African branch began in 1966, and a Welsh branch in 1967.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Ethel Thurston founded a United States branch in New York.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] A BWC branch in India was started in 1974.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] By 1975, there were branches set up in Durban, Pretoria and Cape Town in South Africa, Kenya, the Netherlands, Ireland and further United Kingdom branches in Lancashire, Leeds, East Midlands, Edinburgh and Glasgow.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Finland began its own branch in 1978 and Hong Kong in 1981.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] In 1969, BWC became associated with Compassion in World Farming.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] BWC was supported by its president Lord Dowding and vice presidents, who included Michaela Denis, Spike Milligan and his wife Patricia Ridgeway (Paddy), Brigid Brophy, Maureen Duffy, Tony Britton, Grace Cooke, Rupert Davies, Harry Edwards, Dr.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Barbe Baker, Eva Batt, Rukmini Devi Arundale**,** Patrick Moore and others.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Models gathered to support BWC fashion shows.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] In 1970, Dowding asked former top fur model Celia Hammond to observe the seal cull off the Gulf of St Lawrence, Canada, to help raise awareness on behalf of BWC.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Due to the rapid growth in demand for BWC cosmetics, which caused considerable production problems, Dowding's son, David Whiting became marketing and production director of BWC Ltd in early 1970 until 1973.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Whiting also led BWC in expanding its activities, by launching international investigations into the illegal trade and cruel exploitation of animals.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Reports in the press dubbed him ‘The Animal Spy’, as he made the hard facts of the poaching, smuggling, slaughter and abuse of animals for the fashion and cosmetic's industry freely available to the public and industry alike.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] The cosmetic company was later taken over by Grenville Hawkins and Joseph Piccioni.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Later, in 1978, Piccioni became the managing director of BWC Ltd in Great Britain.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] With his business expertise and dedication to animal rights, Piccioni helped lead BWC Ltd to launch its lines in the United States in 1989.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] In 1979, Dr Ethel Thurston, head of BWC (U.S.A.) coordinated a week of anti-fur protests in New York, with guests Lady Dowding and actress Gretchen Wyler**,** to coincide with the American International Fur Fair.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] The effort is remembered as the beginning of the United States anti-fur movement.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Dowding remained director of BWC Ltd until shortly before the educational charitable trust and the cosmetics company became separate organisations in 1980.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Dowding resigned as president from BWC in 1981.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] BWC's products are free of parabens, gluten, S.L.S, PEG, toluene, formaldehyde and phthalates.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] Although millions of animals are killed each year as a result of animal testing of cosmetics, Beauty Without Cruelty advocates animal rights and argues that the results of animal testing are often unreliable and can not be applied to humans.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] BWC focuses on vegan and "natural" products that cannot chemically harm humans and do not need to be tested on animals.
[src:beauty-without-cruelty/beauty-without-cruelty] BWC has worked to support the Humane Cosmetics Act on its mission to end cosmetic animal testing in the United States.
